author_ssm: Hillel Arnold. Finding aid by Hillel Arnold, Erika Gottfried and Michael Nash.
unittitle_ssm: The Daily Worker and the Daily World Negatives Collection
abstract_ssm: The Daily Worker was established as the Communist Party USA's daily newspaper in 1924.   As the official organ of the Communist Party USA (CPUSA), the Daily Worker's editorial positions reflected the policies of the party while also attempting to speak to the broad left-wing community in the United States that included labor, civil rights, and peace activists.  The newspaper has had a succession of names and has been published in varying frequencies between daily to weekly over the course of its existence. In 2010 it ceased print publication and became an online weekly publication titled the People's World.  The Daily Worker and the Daily World Negatives Collection contains printed photographic images produced through a variety of processes, created and collected by the photography editors of the Daily Worker and its successor newspapers as a means of maintaining an organized collection of images for use in publication.  The collection dates from 1930 to 2006, with the bulk of the material dating from 1930 to 1948 and from 1968 to 1990.  The images depict people, groups, and events associated with the CPUSA.  The collection contains approximately 670,000 photographic negatives in various formats; contact sheets and log sheets related to 35 millimeter negatives; and several hundred slides. NOTE: Access to Series I and Series II is closed through 2025 pending digitization.

unittitle_ssm: New York Committee for Trade Union Action and Democracy Picket New York Central Labor Council Delegate Meeting in Protest of Cooperation with Wage Freeze Policies, Roosevelt Hall, 17th Street and Union Square West, New York, New York. Photographer note regarding frames 23 and 24: "Several Central Labor Council goons jumped me at this point for photographing them hassling a cop. One fascist/racist goon tore the camera from me and smashed it to the sidewalk. The camera body and a small flash unit were badly broken. I could take no action against them because I wasn't sure who did it." Photos by Bill Andrews.
